rdshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, Anglie","Barkway, Hertfordshire, England":"Barkway, Hertfordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1550–15 May 1589":"1550–15. maj 1589","1550–1589":"1550–1589","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1571–1630":"1571–1630","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1529–1568":"1529–1568","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1568":"1568","11 August 1571":"11. august 1571","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1630":"1630","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1529":"1529","15 May 1589":"15. maj 1589","Churchyard, Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England, Great Britain":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Barley, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, England","Barkway, Hertfordshire, England":"Barkway, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1550–15 May 1589":"1550–15 mei 1589","1550–1589":"1550–1589","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1571–1630":"1571–1630","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1529–1568":"1529–1568","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1568":"1568","11 August 1571":"11 augustus 1571","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1630":"1630","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1529":"1529","15 May 1589":"15 mei 1589","Churchyard, Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Clavering, Essex, England, Great Britain":"Clavering, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barley, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, England","Barkway, Hertfordshire, England":"Barkway, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1550–15 May 1589":"1550–15 May 1589","1550–1589":"1550–1589","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1571–1630":"1571–1630","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1529–1568":"1529–1568","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1568":"1568","11 August 1571":"11 August 1571","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1630":"1630","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1529":"1529","15 May 1589":"15 May 1589","Churchyard, Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England, Great Britain":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Barley, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, England","Barkway, Hertfordshire, England":"Barkway, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"GG","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jian, Ping, Haiping, Huilan, Ling, Ming, Pei, Qiong, Song, Wen, Xun, Yan.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 葛, referring to a ‘type of herbal plant’: (i) said to be from Ge-Tian (葛天), the name of an ancient tribe in China living prior to the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). (ii) from Ge (葛), the name of an ancient state (located in Henan province) during the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). (iii) borne by descendants of Hong Ge Lu (洪葛盧), also known as Hong Pu Lu, who offered support to Emperor Guangwu of Han (5  BC –57  AD ) and made great contributions to the establishment of the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD ). He later transferred the title that had been conferred on him by the emperor to his brother, and migrated to Gou Rong (in present-day Jiangsu province). Some of his descendants inherited Ge (葛), part of his personal name, as their surname. (iv) adopted as a surname by the He Ge (賀葛) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 戈, referring to a ‘kind of weapon’ in ancient China: from Ge (戈), the name of an ancient state (located in Henan province) during the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]},{"name":"Ni","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jian, Pei-Lin, Kong, Min, Ming, Yung, Bin, Cao, Huang, Jing, Wen, Zhen, Biao, Chang, Chi, Quan, Yaping.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 倪, meaning ‘boundary’ or ‘infants’ in ancient Chinese: adopted in order to escape from a feud in place of the Chinese surname 郳, which is also pronounced Ni. The original surname was from Ni (郳), the name of an ancient state, also called Little Zhu (located in Shandong province), granted to the son of Duke Wu of Zhu (ruler of the state of Zhu, died 796  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 賴, see   Lai   1."]},{"name":"Kuh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Math.","Jewish (from Bohemia and Silesia): habitational name from a butcher's shop distinguished by the sign of a cow, German <i>Kuh</i>.","German: from Middle High German <i>kuo</i> ‘cow’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a cowherd or for a dairy or cattle farmer."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Thake GG 11LT was born in 1550, in Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Thake, was 25 and his mother, Agnes Freston, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Tipping. He died on 15 May 1589, in Barkway, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":